
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Can Systems Really Be Taught? (A Socratic Dialogue)
AU  - Oliva, Terence A.
AU  - Capdevielle, Christel M.
Y1  - 1980/04/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1980.4288752
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1980.4288752
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 277
EP  - 280
VL  - 5
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The form of this paper comes from a presentation by Ian Mitroff at the 1976 Annual North American Meetings of the Society for General Systems Research. He used a Socratic dialogue to present several points of view regarding a different subject altogether [Mitroff, 1977]. What we have attempted is a Socratic dialogue between a student and a teacher concerning whether or not systems can be taught. We hope that, during the discussion, the answer emerges as well as an understanding of the nature of systems. Parts of the first portion of the dialogue are taken from Plato's Meno, with appropriate words altered to fit the purpose at hand.
AB  - The form of this paper comes from a presentation by Ian Mitroff at the 1976 Annual North American Meetings of the Society for General Systems Research. He used a Socratic dialogue to present several points of view regarding a different subject altogether [Mitroff, 1977]. What we have attempted is a Socratic dialogue between a student and a teacher concerning whether or not systems can be taught. We hope that, during the discussion, the answer emerges as well as an understanding of the nature of systems. Parts of the first portion of the dialogue are taken from Plato's Meno, with appropriate words altered to fit the purpose at hand.
